Tsitouras' (2011) 6 stage, order 5 Runge-Kutta scheme with a 7 stage order 4 FSAL embedded scheme

Runge–Kutta pairs of orders 5(4) using the minimal set of simplifying assumptions,
by Ch. Tsitouras, TEI of Chalkis, Dept. of Applied Sciences, GR34400, Psahna, Greece.

85-digit coefficients obtained from Peter Stone's website,
http://www.peterstone.name/Maplepgs/Maple/nmthds/RKcoeff/Runge_Kutta_schemes/RK5/RKcoeff5n_1.pdf

Floating-point interpolant coefficients obtained from,
https://github.com/SciML/OrdinaryDiffEq.jl/blob/master/src/tableaus/low_order_rk_tableaus.jl

Based on the interpolant coefficients for the last stage, I deduced that the fourth-order interpolant
is the one that can be derived via the Nystrom transformation algorithm. And I was right. Using Peter Stone's
85-digit coefficients, I obtained the 85-digit version of the interpolant coefficients. Converting them to
standard floats yielded exactly the ones I got from the SciML github page.

Nystrom Transformation Algorithm is described here:
P.W. Sharp, J.M. Fine, A contrast of direct and transformed Nyström pairs, Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics,
Volume 42, Issue 3, 1992, Pages 293-308, ISSN 0377-0427, https://doi.org/10.1016/0377-0427(92)90082-9.
(https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0377042792900829)
